  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Business and Human Rights: Building local capacity to counter corporate human rights abuses</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Africa, as well other parts of the world, globalisation triggered that non-state actors including transnational corporations and other businesses have gradually become more powerful and influential, bringing new challenges in the field of human rights. Increasingly, local communities have been confronted with human rights abuses committed by businesses, whether through poor labour conditions, forced evictions or the destruction of their livelihoods as a result of e.g. logging, mining and pollution. Although governments have the obligation to protect people from such abuses, many fail to do so. Over the years, the United Nations human rights machinery has tried to clarify the respective roles and responsibilities of governments and businesses with regard to protecting and respecting human rights. Yet, there are still few effective mechanisms at (inter)national level that prevent and address corporate abuses. Moreover, local people and communities often do not know their rights or how to seek justice for the corporate abuses they are confronted with. They lack access to information; are excluded from decision-making processes; or face ineffective legal systems and/or corruption.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">To help local organisations, activists, and grassroots communities better understand their rights against corporate interests, as well as the respective roles and responsibilities of businesses and governments, AINL/HURICAP has developed a capacity-building package comprised of a handbook series and training modules. While the training package is in its final development stage, it needs further testing and piloting, which is on hold due to the covid-19 crisis.</narrative>
  </description>
